# Spec Archive Workflow

## Purpose
Finalize an applied spec-driven change: merge spec deltas into the source-of-truth specs, merge the feature branch, archive the change workspace, and clean up. This is phase 3 of 3 in the SDD lifecycle: propose → apply → archive. Requires the change PR to be approved and ready to merge.

## Steps to Generate

### 1. Verify Apply Phase Complete
// if any task in tasks.md is unchecked
Stop and return to the apply workflow:
- All tasks in `tasks.md` must be checked or explicitly skipped
- All tests must pass on the feature branch
- The PR must be approved and ready to merge
- If any condition fails, do not archive

### 2. Apply Spec Deltas to Source-of-Truth
For each delta file in `openspec/changes/<change-id>/specs/<capability>/spec.md`:
- Read the corresponding `openspec/specs/<capability>/spec.md` (or create it if new capability)
- For each `## ADDED Requirements` section: append the new requirements
- For each `## MODIFIED Requirements` section: replace the existing requirement with the revised version
- For each `## REMOVED Requirements` section: delete those requirements from the spec
- Preserve other existing requirements untouched

### 3. Validate Merged Specs
// turbo
Confirm the merged specs are well-formed:
- Each requirement has at least one Given/When/Then scenario
- No duplicate requirement names within a capability
- All capability directories have a `spec.md` file
- Markdown is valid (no broken sections, headings consistent)

### 4. Commit Spec Consolidation
// turbo
Stage and commit the consolidated specs:
- `git add openspec/specs/`
- Commit message: `archive: <change-id> - consolidate spec deltas`
- This commit lives on the feature branch alongside the implementation

### 5. Move Change to Archive
// turbo
Archive the change workspace with date stamp:
- Capture today's date in `YYYY-MM-DD` format
- Move `openspec/changes/<change-id>/` to `openspec/changes/archive/YYYY-MM-DD-<change-id>/`
- This preserves history and proposal artifacts indefinitely
- Commit: `archive: move <change-id> to archive/`

### 6. Merge Feature Branch
// turbo
Merge using the project's preferred strategy:
- Squash, merge commit, or rebase per repo convention
- Use the change-id and one-line summary as the merge title
- Reference closed issues in the merge commit body
- Verify the merge appears on the base branch

### 7. Delete Feature Branch
// turbo
Clean up the branch:
- Delete the local branch: `git branch -d feature/<change-id>`
- Delete the remote branch: `git push origin --delete feature/<change-id>`
- Confirm branch is gone with `git branch -a`

### 8. Verify Deployment
// if the project has CD pipeline
Confirm the change reaches the target environment:
- Watch CI/CD pipeline complete successfully
- Run smoke tests against the deployed environment
- Monitor error rates and key metrics for regressions
- If issues appear, prepare a rollback or fix proposal

### 9. Communicate Completion
Notify relevant stakeholders:
- Update the original ticket/issue with merge link
- Note any follow-up tasks that emerged during apply
- Document any deployment caveats or required actions for users

## Anti-patterns
- Archiving while tasks are still unchecked
- Merging deltas to specs without validation
- Skipping the archive move (specs lose audit trail)
- Force-pushing to the base branch during merge
- Deleting the change directory instead of archiving (loses history)
- Merging the feature branch before specs are consolidated
- Skipping deployment verification on production-affecting changes
